{"id":"physics/0408061","submitter":"Anders Levermann","authors":"Anders Levermann and Alexa Griesel","title":"Solution of a Model for the Oceanic Pycnocline Depth: Scaling of\n  Overturning Strength and Meridional Pressure Difference","comments":"Geophysical Research Letters (2004), accepted. See also\n  http://www.pik-potsdam.de/~anders","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1029/2004GL020678","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.ao-ph physics.geo-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We present an analysis of the model by Gnanadesikan [1999] for the pycnocline\ndepth in the ocean. An analytic solution for the overturning strength as a\nfunction of the meridional pressure difference is derived and used to discuss\ntheir mutual scaling. We show that scaling occurs only in two unphysical\nregimes of the model. In the absence of the Southern Ocean (SO) processes, i.e.\nfor a northern overturning cell, the volume transport is proportional to the\nsquare root of the pressure difference. Linear scaling is seen when the\noverturning is restricted entirely to the SO, i.e. when no northern downwelling\nexists. For comparison, we present simulations with the coupled climate model\nCLIMBER-3$\\alpha$ which show linear scaling over a large regime of pressure\ndifferences in the North Atlantic (NA). We conclude that the pycnocline model\nis not able to reproduce the linear scaling between its two central variables,\npressure and volume transport.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 13 Aug 2004 07:23:50 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-26"}
{"id":"physics/0408062","submitter":"Anders Levermann","authors":"Anders Levermann, Alexa Griesel, Matthias Hofmann, Marisa Montoya, and\n  Stefan Rahmstorf","title":"Dynamic sea level changes following changes in the thermohaline\n  circulation","comments":"Climate Dynamics (2004), submitted. See also\n  http://www.pik-potsdam.de/~anders","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1007/s00382-004-0505-y","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.ao-ph physics.geo-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  Using the coupled climate model CLIMBER-3a, we investigate changes in sea\nsurface elevation due to a weakening of the thermohaline circulation (THC). In\naddition to a global sea level rise due to a warming of the deep sea, this\nleads to a regional dynamic sea level change which follows\nquasi-instantaneously any change in the ocean circulation. We show that the\nmagnitude of this dynamic effect can locally reach up to ~1m, depending on the\ninitial THC strength. In some regions the rate of change can be up to 20-25\nmm/yr. The emerging patterns are discussed with respect to the oceanic\ncirculation changes. Most prominent is a south-north gradient reflecting the\nchanges in geostrophic surface currents. Our results suggest that an analysis\nof observed sea level change patterns could be useful for monitoring the THC\nstrength.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 13 Aug 2004 07:33:30 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-10"}
